metadata.name: Shawq #70
metadata.description: Shawq is a simple generative geometric piece made with pure p5.js and a WebGL shader.

metadata.name: Knockout #159
metadata.description:
An exploration of screen printing techniques and how these effects can be achieved in generative work. The halftone effect works by placing very small dots next to each other to give the illusion of new shades and hues. Each Knockout samples three colors for the main composition and runs small sections of the canvas back through the machine after shuffling the base palette. The secondary passes vary in size, creating interesting emergent patterns on the overlap.

Press 's' in live view to save a .png

Built and tested with Chrome on Apple silicon. Some outputs may take up to 20s on slower machines.

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Space & Time #15
metadata.description: A set of generative explorations made between Jan/22 and Feb/22.

metadata.name: Sketch F #130
metadata.description:
Sketch is an open-ended series. Works evolve as I code a generative project, sometimes drastically. Intermediate works usually don't see the light of day - they get archived and forgotten. This series is snapshots of different forms along the way - each standing alone, but also part of a larger meandering work flow. The word Sketch implies incompleteness. This project may end up being two works, or it could evolve for years. Part of the joy of generative art is never knowing what's around the corner. I have no set schedule. There may be multiple Sketches released a week, or it could be weeks or months between drops. I have no idea where Sketch is heading and there is no guarantee of cohesiveness from Sketch to Sketch. Color palettes and forms will change as new ideas are explored.

Sketch F(ree). A gift to all Sketch A-E collectors. The underlying grid structure from A-E remains, but more variation on size and distribution is added. Many more color palettes are introduced. Grid size, padding, and colors vary.

A zigzag is a pattern made up of small corners at variable angles, though constant within the zigzag, tracing a path between two parallel lines; it can be described as both jagged and fairly regular.
In geometry, this pattern is described as a skew apeirogon. From the point of view of symmetry, a regular zigzag can be generated from a simple motif like a line segment by repeated application of a glide reflection.

Another name for the pattern is "Herringbone" FYI ğŸ¤“

There's a chance no lines are shown at all, this is intentional, as I love "bugs" ğŸª²

metadata.name: Gray Copper Swallow #172
metadata.description:
"Gray Copper Swallow" is a p5.js project where isometric shapes are placed and have their size and color adjusted based on an underlying grid of shapes and colors. Each form is derived from the lightness or darkness of a particular pixel in the underlying grid. Many renders remind me of cityscapes with buildings, roads, and bridges.

Press s to save the image.

metadata.name: BWEEPS  #178
metadata.description:
A minimalist, black-and-white generative profile picture (PFP) created to commemorate one-year anniversary of Bwople project by Gengoya. The artwork is derived from an initial sketch of Bwople which, despite being not the one that was chosen, still managed to captivate interests. The project provides a unique glimpse into an alternate universe in which Bwople could have been represented.

All images are hand-drawn work by Gengoya and composed by Vector Recite using PureSpider's fxhash-pfp maker tool.

To download the full size image on fx(hash):
- Click "open" below the image
- Left click on the image, a "Download image" button will appear on the bottom right.
- Click the "Download image" button.

"Cheerful Obscure" is the 26th project I have minted on fxhash. For this project, I experimented with filling all the shapes with gradients. This is a gradient, that is a gradient, gradients everywhere!

metadata.name: Tangled #55
metadata.description:
"Tangled" is a generative art project that explores the emergent behaviour of simple shapes moving according to a random flow field. While the final result is always constrained to the shape of a circle, the variation within is endless.

Instructions:
Press "p" to pause the animation.
In live mode, press 1 through 5 to save a PNG version of the final result. The following resolutions are available:
1: 400 x 400 (ideal for Twitter PFP)
2: 1000 x 1000
3: 2000 x 2000
4: 4000 x 4000
5: 5000 x 5000
Please be patient, generating the PNG may take some time!

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: Physarum Logo #971
metadata.description:
These past few months have been a great experience and with the beta ending, I wanted to create a piece to thank all collectors and pay tribute to this great platform. 

The piece is based on a physarum simulation with a couple of tweaks, such as continuous behavioural changes and an extra information layer that further manipulates the physarum.

There are ~262k particles simulated in parallel, so it is quite GPU heavy. 

Each piece features one of 12 different colour pallets, the text and a couple of cell-like bodies running around the screen.

Controls: 
S - Save image
H - Hide Text
Click/Touch - Spawn particles

Disclaimer: This is nothing official by the platform itself, merely a tribute by an artist and fan. 

With all that said: Thank you to everyone, and see you in 1.0 !

metadata.name: fields #45
metadata.description:
A generative sketchbook of ideas for a sculpture garden.

Fields builds off Stan Allen's seminal essay "Field Conditions" in which he laid out a prototypical theory of architectural field schemes. Field Conditions are opposed to figural or object-based compositional strategies and approach a site from a systemic point of view. These fields contain a range of possible wall-types. Some produce enclosures, while others dictate a wandering path.

Built with p5.js
By office ca
2022
